The paper deals with local computation algorithms for graph problems, which are typically studied in the computer science subfields of data structures (cs.DS), discrete mathematics (cs.DM), computational complexity (cs.CC), graph theory (cs.GT), and computational geometry (cs.CG). The focus on non-constant degrees suggests that the paper may be more relevant to subfields that deal with general graphs rather than regular graphs, which is why cs.DS and cs.DM are the most likely categories. The use of randomized algorithms and approximation algorithms suggests that cs.CC and cs.CG are also possible categories. Finally, the paper's focus on specific graph problems such as maximal independent sets and maximum matching suggests that cs.GT is also a possible category.
